{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17644338","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17644338"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:04:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:04:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18042"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18042","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18042"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10756"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74133"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10756","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10756"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18042"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59624"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8407"},{"type":"tags","id":"8701"},{"type":"tags","id":"10208"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25093"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25097"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74133","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74133"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EBone tissue forms through two distinct developmental processes: endochondral and intramembranous ossification. These mechanisms result in different types of bone formation throughout the skeleton.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about osteogenesis is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Osteoblasts deposit osteoid during bone formation","Endochondral ossification directly converts mesenchymal tissue into bone","Intramembranous ossification involves a cartilage model","Osteoclasts are responsible for forming new bone","Endochondral ossification occurs primarily in flat bones"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct statement is that \u003Cstrong\u003Eosteoblasts deposit osteoid during bone formation\u003C/strong\u003E. Osteoblasts are cells that synthesise and secrete the organic components of the bone matrix, known as osteoid, which later becomes mineralised to form mature bone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndochondral ossification directly converts mesenchymal tissue into bone\u003C/strong\u003E - This process involves the replacement of a cartilage model with bone, not direct conversion\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntramembranous ossification involves a cartilage model\u003C/strong\u003E - This process involves the direct formation of bone from mesenchymal tissue without a cartilage intermediate\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteoclasts are responsible for forming new bone\u003C/strong\u003E - Osteoclasts are involved in bone resorption, not formation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndochondral ossification occurs primarily in flat bones\u003C/strong\u003E - It primarily occurs in long bones, while intramembranous ossification occurs in flat bones\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The process of endochondral ossification transforms cartilage into bone tissue and is the main mechanism for long bone development.","Flat bones form through intramembranous ossification, where bone develops directly from connective tissue precursors.","The bone matrix protein osteoid is secreted by osteoblasts and subsequently becomes mineralised bone tissue."],"references":["Gartner, L. P. (2020). Textbook of histology e-book: Textbook of histology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Baig MA, Bacha D. Histology, Bone. 2023 May 1. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31082176","Blumer MJF. Bone tissue and histological and molecular events during development of the long bones. Ann Anat. 2021 May;235:151704. doi: 10.1016/j.aanat.2021.151704. Epub 2021 Feb 16. PMID: 33600952","Florencio-Silva R, Sasso GR, Sasso-Cerri E, Sim\u00f5es MJ, Cerri PS. Biology of Bone Tissue: Structure, Function, and Factors That Influence Bone Cells. Biomed Res Int. 2015;2015:421746. doi: 10.1155/2015/421746. Epub 2015 Jul 13. PMID: 26247020; PMCID: PMC4515490"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59624"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18042"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59624","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59624"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T21:23:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-24T21:37:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10756"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74133"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attr